## What Is This?

ECR repositories default to `scan_on_push: false`. Images sit in the registry for months without a vulnerability scan. When a CVE is published, there is no way to know which images are affected without manually triggering scans across every repository.

The second gap is lifecycle policies. Without them, ECR repositories accumulate images indefinitely. Old untagged images from months ago remain deployable. Registry storage costs grow unchecked. Log4Shell-era images sit there, pullable by anyone with ECR access.

ECR offers two scanning modes: **Basic** (Clair-based, OS packages only) and **Enhanced** (Amazon Inspector, covers OS packages and application dependencies — npm, pip, Maven). Most accounts use basic scanning, which misses application-level CVEs entirely.

